<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910416-0013</DOCNO><DOCID>910416-0013.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Automatic Data Processing Inc.:   Firm's Per-Share Earnings   Rose 14% in Third Quarter</HL><DATE>04/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   AUD</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)</RE><LP>   Automatic Data Processing Inc. posted a 14% increase inthird-quarter per-share earnings, after double-digit growthat its employer services unit.   In the quarter that ended March 31, ADP reported net roseto $69.7 million, or $1 a share, from $65 million, or 88cents a share. Revenue rose 4.2%, to $490.9 million, from$470.8 million.</LP><TEXT>   The independent computing services firm, based inRoseland, N.J., said the earnings increase came on fewershares outstanding; ADP purchased about 5.3 million commonshares during the year. The purchase of treasury stockreduced earnings and revenue growth because of the resultingreduction in interest income. The results don't reflect arecently announced 2-for-1 stock split effective May 1.   ADP said employer services, which represent almost 60% ofits revenue, continued double-digit revenue growth. Despitethe weakened economy, year-to-date sales to new clients areahead of a year ago, while client retention remained flat,ADP said. The company said it continues to expect a modestincrease in full-year revenue, and is &quot;confident&quot; per-shareearnings for the year would &quot;clearly exceed 10%.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>